        <div class="buzz-card">
          <span class="buzz-card-tag">Music</span>
          <h3 class="buzz-card-hed">Olivia Rodrigo's Third Album Is Stranger and Better Than Billed</h3>
          <p class="buzz-card-body">Released June 12, <em>You Seem Pretty Sad for a Girl So in Love</em> is Rodrigo's most ambitious record — marketed as a concept album about anxiety in love, it shapeshifts mid-listen into something rawer and less comfortable than that pitch. Rolling Stone called the opener "a pure dopamine rush." Billboard said it "feels like a living, breathing thing."</p>
          <div class="buzz-row">
            <span class="buzz-label">Buzz</span>
            <div class="buzz-bar-track"><div class="buzz-bar-fill" style="width:80%"></div></div>
            <span class="buzz-score">8/10</span>
          </div>
          <div class="sources">
            <a class="source-link" href="https://rollingstone.com" target="_blank">Rolling Stone</a>
            <span class="source-sep">·</span>
            <a class="source-link" href="https://billboard.com" target="_blank">Billboard</a>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="buzz-card">
          <span class="buzz-card-tag">Style</span>
          <h3 class="buzz-card-hed">JW Anderson × Diadora Is the Sneaker Collab That Actually Earns It</h3>
          <p class="buzz-card-body">JW Anderson's debut with Italian brand Diadora revives the 1975 Equipe runner — handmade in Montebelluna, in four suede colourways, with no visible logo worship. Highsnobiety called it "a collision between Anderson's offbeat fashion instinct and Diadora's slower, deeply Italian relationship with sport, craft, and archive." This is what a fashion collab is supposed to feel like.</p>
          <div class="buzz-row">
            <span class="buzz-label">Buzz</span>
            <div class="buzz-bar-track"><div class="buzz-bar-fill" style="width:70%"></div></div>
            <span class="buzz-score">7/10</span>
          </div>
          <div class="sources">
            <a class="source-link" href="https://highsnobiety.com" target="_blank">Highsnobiety</a>
            <span class="source-sep">·</span>
            <a class="source-link" href="https://wwd.com" target="_blank">WWD</a>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="buzz-card">
          <span class="buzz-card-tag">Culture</span>
          <h3 class="buzz-card-hed">Vulture Did a Live Festival in New York the Weekend the Knicks Won the Title</h3>
          <p class="buzz-card-body">Vulture Festival at Tribeca (June 13–14, SVA Theatre) brought marquee conversations and live podcast recordings to Manhattan the same weekend the city was celebrating its first NBA championship in over half a century. The timing was almost cinematic — New York genuinely having a cultural moment across sport, media, and the street simultaneously.</p>
          <div class="buzz-row">
            <span class="buzz-label">Buzz</span>
            <div class="buzz-bar-track"><div class="buzz-bar-fill" style="width:60%"></div></div>
